"Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Barden Park in Tonbridge, Kent, or Bardown in Ticehurst, Sussex, or Berden in Essex.","English: habitational name from any of the places in North and Yorkshire named Barden, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ (or the derived adjective <i>beren</i>) + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’.","English: variant of   Bardon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bearden","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Barden  ,   Bardon   2, or from places in Devon and Cornwall called Beardon, from Old English <i>burh</i> ‘manor’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’. In the British Isles the surname is now rare."]},{"name":"Bardin","meanings":["English: variant of   Barden  .","Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Bairdín</b>, see   Barden   4.","French: from a pet form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bardo</i>, from <i>barta</i> ‘battle axe’ (see   Bard   1)."]},{"name":"Bardon","meanings":["English: habitational name from Bardon in Leicestershire, named with Old English <i>berg</i> ‘hill, mound, barrow’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’, meaning ‘barrow hill’.","English: variant of   Barden  .","Irish: Anglicized form of <i>Ó Bárdáin</i>, see   Barden   4."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":38,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Lady William de Barden was born in 1290, in Yorkshire, England. She had at least 1 son with William de Barden."},"et":{"1290–":"1290–Surnud","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1300":"1300","1285":"1285","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","York